Class Maze

java.lang.Object
  Maze

public class Maze
extends java.lang.Object

Data structure for the Maze program.

The class Maze serves both as the data structure for a maze to be played and the place where the logic for the maze solver resides. You are supposed to modify various parts of this file.

The two constructors for the Maze structure populate data that you must define so that the various get methods for the structure of the maze work properly. One constructor that reads the maze structure from a file is already implemented. You will have to implement the constructor that generates a random maze of a given number of rows and columns.

The solve() method needs to be implemented, and will contain the logic for the maze solver. It should run a depth-first search from the start of the maze (cell [0,0]). As the solver is running, it should update the display with its location using the MazePlay.setState() method. The MazePlay GUI will reflect the solver state whenever this method is called by coloring parts of the maze in the GUI.

solve

public void solve(MazePlay player)
           throws java.lang.ThreadDeath
Runs a depth-first search to explore the maze, starting at the top-left cell (row 0, column 0).

You must implement this method.

The parameter player given to this method gives access to the MazePlay object that represents the GUI for the maze. You should use the setState() function of MazePlay to keep track of where your solver is going during its exploration. This method is also hooked into the thread-control mechanism that keeps the solver running.

Parameters:
player - A reference to the MazePlay object that represents the GUI displaying the maze
Throws:
java.lang.ThreadDeath - if the player window gets closed during execution of the search
